XVS7zN3oi2c.title: Combination Play and Finishing SSG | Birmingham City Professional Soccer Training
XVS7zN3oi2c.description:
Ainsley Cooper, the then U10 Lead Coach for Birmingham City FC Academy completes his combination and finishing session with a small-sided game.

Ainsley set up the players in small attacking groups of 3v3 with the aim to attack and combine together.

One team starts as the attacking team and receives from the goalkeeper’s distribution. They combine together to attack towards the goal and try to score. The opposition starts as the defending team and tries to win the ball back. If they win it, they try and play into the end zone. If they succeed in getting to the end zone, they become the attacking team and the reds become the defending team.

Players need to be able to recognise where the space is – if they press high, they leave space behind to run into.

pzznV7MQJEY.title: Technical Receiving Practice | Leyton Orient Professional Soccer Training
pzznV7MQJEY.description:
Scott Boyle, the then U13/14 Lead Phase Coach at Leyton Orient,  delivered a session on Pressing from the front, with a subtopic of switching play.
Ryan, the then U13/14 Assistant Coach lead the warm-up with a technical practice to work on receiving the ball and checking shoulders, but still with a pressing element.

The first activity is a two-touch technical practice, working in a circle the player needs to run into the middle and pass the player on their right. When you pass you are 'pressing' the next man to force them to take their first touch off line before playing to the next player.

This progresses into two-touch or one-touch, giving the players a decision on which is best to take.

Ryan gives the players plenty of opportunities to 'fix' and solve problems. He lets the session play giving players the chance to organise and lead from within the session.

Ryan moves onto a different passing and receiving practice, the next activity forces the player to step out to receive the ball, practice adding disguise to their movements to receive.

The final progression sees the players again playing short quick combinations off 1 and two touches in the technical practice.

aG1xlQvIx7o.title: Carshalton Crossing & Finishing Practice | Professional Soccer Training
aG1xlQvIx7o.description:
Kieth Boanas, is working with the Academy 1st Years on individual technical skills, turning, crossing and finishing.

Keith is using the practice to implement the ethos of crossing and beating defenders in the wide-area while working on players technical ability.

The ball starts at the halfway line with the attacking players, alternating between the left and right side of the pitch.
Then there are 3 steps to the practice:

1. The attackers will receive the ball and dribble down the pitch and cross into the 18yard box, where two midfielders and two defenders will work 2v2.

2. When the ball is played out or scored, another ball will be put into play from the goal for the attacking player on the other side of the pitch to react to and cross into the 18yard box.

3. The final ball is played from the halfway line for the middle line to work 2v2 to cross and score.

The aim of the session is for the players to get lots of crossing and finishing in and work in lots of technical practice and work on reaction.

Finding feet with the throw
Using their body to protect the ball
Body shape to receive to turn
Getting your body over the ball to keep it low

jrbcHZwB6EA.title: Brøndby 1v1 soccer practice | Professional Soccer Training
jrbcHZwB6EA.description:
Here is a 1v1 practice from Danish giants, Brøndby IF. These 1v1 sessions are split into 2 phases. This is a high-intensity session, great for a high load day, and also ties into Brøndby's pressing philosophy to have a tactical element too.

Phase 1: The goal is for the attacker to get into the scoring zone to score, if the defender can win the ball can they counter-attack the opposite end.

Phase 2: Both players start at the same end, the attacker must cross the scoring line to turn and attack the goals where he came from. This challenges the attacking player to free up space to turn and then attack the defender 1v1.

This sessions bring out quality technical 1v1 and physical outcomes while working on both players speed and turning skills, and gives them different scenarios to play.

DnAquYT-uj0.title: Dinamo Zagreb U13 1v1 & 2v2 Soccer Practice
DnAquYT-uj0.description:
Here is a simple but very effective 1v1 & 2v2 practice I saw the Dinamo Zagreb U13’s do. The coach split the group into 2, the assistant taking the other and ran this session. You could easily do the same if you were coaching by yourself, just have the pitches side by side.
The set up and the rules are simple. The coach allowed a pass through one of the gates to score. I was thinking it would be a good progression to insist on dribbling through one of the gates.
The coach eventually progressed this to a 2v2, in the same space. The players really had to work hard off the ball to support the player in possession.
As you will see from the video, there are lots of excellent outcomes in this session as the boys use their dribbling skills and turns to beat the defenders. To give you an idea of the how this session sat in the bigger picture, the coach progressed this into 5v5s and then a 10v10 at the end. This was a really good example of using Small Sided Games (SSG’s) to stagger a session and get lots of quality technical outcomes.

CuR4ms1_vfc.title: MPFC Coach's Pass - Harry Watling West Ham Academy Coach Football Cricket
CuR4ms1_vfc.description:
This Coach’s Pass session is delivered by Harry Watling. Harry is a West Ham Academy Coach, here he is working with the APD Football Scholars.
Harry’s session is a Football Cricket defending practice with an attacking element.

There are four phases to this practice with Harry coaching the defending team:

Phase 1 – Midfielders make five passes then play into the number 9 before the ball goes out wide. Harry coaches the three defenders on their positioning as the ball comes in creating a 3v3 in the box.

Phase 2 – Defenders ‘flip’ positioning, so tucked-in full back from Phase 1 now becomes the first CB and back player uses inside of his post as a reference point. There are two balls to defend in this phase – one from either side.

Phase 3 – A third ball is introduced from the middle area where midfielders can drive at the heart and shoot or play out wide. Depending on the decision the midfielder makes affects defenders positioning.

Phase 4 – An extra midfield player is introduced to the defending team to pick up and clear any loose balls.
